doc.title: Airfreight & Surface Transportation Week 34 Rail Metrics: YoY carload comps a bit muddled, but volumes and service generally looking good
doc.source_uri: 2025-08-29/Week 34 Rail Metrics YoY carload comps a bit muddled but volumes and service generally looking goodWeek 34 Rail Metrics _2025-08-29

passages.text: Rail volumes are accelerating, with L4W carloads +140bps YoY compared to the prior week's (Week 33) +50bps YoY. Aggregate L4W carload growth across all segments has picked up from the prior week's levels, and all are now in positive growth territory (whereas last week Merchandise was down a few bps YoY). Western rails are experiencing a bit of a drag particularly from Intermodal, though this comes on hard comps from last year's diversions away from East Coast ports ahead of strike risk. Service across rails is looking good on a YoY- basis, though NSC's trains appear to still be running a bit slower YoY. An overall improving volume and service backdrop is welcome news, but market attention remains focused more on the long- term implications of mergers rather than near- term margin trends. Download of underlying data can be found here.

Carloads (Exhibit 2). Total North American carloads have seen a meaningful acceleration in growth from the prior week's (i.e. Week 33) L4W levels, going from just +50bps YoY to +140bps YoY this past week. This was driven by sizable jumps in L4W YoY carload growth at the Canadian rails, which actually saw the highest YoY growth levels of the whole group by a significant amount (next largest is NSC, at just +1% YoY). We'd point out, though, that this time last year was around the Canadian rail labor dispute that led to a gradual shutdown of shipments to avoid stranded cargo / an eventual full shutdown on Aug. 22 that lasted a few days (Week 34 comps incorporate these dates, including the start of the shutdown). As such, CN / CPKC have easier comps right now, helping to bolster their numbers. Meanwhile, Western rails UNP / BNSF actually saw slight slowdowns from Week 33 levels and are now the only two rails in L4W negative YoY growth territory. Western rail YoY slowdowns from last week were driven by weaker Coal and Intermodal numbers; in contrast to the Canadian players, which saw solid improvement across all segments, particularly Intermodal, vs. last week. Eastern rails have improved slightly vs. last week's L4W YoY growth levels for total carloads, but improvement for both is less than 1%, and the drivers of the pickup vary between the two rails. For NSC, Intermodal and Merchandise are looking better than they were in Week 33, whereas for CSX, improvement is coming mostly from Coal and a bit from Merchandise. Now when it comes to the Western and Eastern rails, we'd point out that they too experienced labor dispute drama around this time last year, with threats of an East Coast port strike that was potentially going to unfold on Oct. 1, leading some shippers to divert volume to the West during weeks leading up to that point. As such, Western rails face tougher Intermodal comps during this period / weeks to come, which helps explain the weaker YoY performance vs. peers right now.

Implied full- quarter performance vs. estimates (Exhibit 3). Using QTD YoY growth rates we arrive at an implied full 3Q forecast that suggests volume is generally looking better than current street estimates (but slightly below consensus for CPKC).

Service (Exhibit 4- Exhibit 23). 4WMA speed / dwell are generally improving YoY across the rails. NSC, however, has recently been dealing with slower train speeds (negative 4WMA YoY train speeds for a number of weeks); good news is NSC dwell is down YoY. CPKC is still lagging peers on YoY dwell, now just flat YoY while all others show improvement.
O - Outperform, M - Market-Perform, U - Underperform, NR - Not Rated, CS - Coverage Suspended
Source: Bloomberg, Bernstein estimates and analysis.

The rail network is running well, but volume trends are expected to soften as we lap tougher comps. The picture is going to get a little fuzzier as we navigate the remainder of the year, but this should matter less for the stocks as the market focuses more on merger outcomes.

Source: Visible Alpha, Bernstein Analysis

Note: All BNSF metrics use a repeat of the prior week's data for the current week because the company is slow to post updated data relative to peers. BNSF is the only railroad mentioned that is not covered by Bernstein.

- Total North American carloads have seen a meaningful acceleration in growth from the prior week's (i.e. Week 33) L4W levels, going from just \(+50\) bps YoY to \(+140\) bps YoY this past week. This was driven by sizable jumps in L4W YoY carload growth at the Canadian rails (Week 33 CN=+4.7%, CPKC=+0.4%; now Week 34 CN=+8.7%, CPKC=+5.6%). These also represent the highest YoY growth levels of the whole group by a significant amount (next largest is at NSC, at just \(+1\%\) YoY growth in the L4W period). We would point out, though, that this time last year was around the time of the Canadian rail labor dispute that led to a gradual shutdown of shipments to avoid stranded cargo / an eventual full shutdown on August \(22^{\text{nd}}\) that lasted a few days (Week 34 comps incorporate these dates, including the start of the shutdown). As such, CN and CPKC have easier comps right now, helping to bolster their numbers.

- Strong Canadian rail performance comes in contrast to performance at the Western rails, UNP and BNSF, which actually saw slight slowdowns from the prior week's (Week 33) levels and are now the only two rails in negative YoY growth territory over the L4Ws. Western rail YoY slowdowns from last week were driven by weaker Coal and Intermodal numbers; in contrast to the Canadian players, which saw solid improvement across all segments, particularly Intermodal, vs. last week. Eastern rails have improved slightly vs. last week's L4W YoY growth levels for total carloads, but improvement for both is less than 1%, and the drivers of the pickup vary between the two rails. For NSC, Intermodal and Merchandise are looking better than they were in Week 33, whereas for CSX, improvement is coming mostly from Coal and a bit from Merchandise. Now when it comes to the Western and Eastern rails, we would point out that they too experienced labor dispute drama around this time last year, with threats of an East Coast port strike that was potentially going to unfold on October \(1^{\text{st}}\) , 2024 leading some shippers to divert volume to West Coast ports during the weeks leading up to that point. As such, Western rails definitely face tougher Intermodal comps during this period and in the weeks to come, which helps explain the weaker YoY performance vs. peers right now.

- Coal volumes have sustained their upward momentum. In the L4Ws, Coal volumes were up \(5.1\%\) YoY, an increase from the \(4.2\%\) growth observed over the last 13 weeks (L13Ws). The Canadian and Eastern rails drove this YoY trend improvement over the period, while Western rails experienced deceleration. Still, UNP lands alongside CN and CPKC as rails with extremely high L4W Coal growth, all showing double-digit YoY growth (while peers are all close to flat or negative).

- Intermodal volumes accelerated their YoY growth over the L4Ws, reaching \(+1.5\%\) , which marks a 30bps increase from L13W levels. CNI, CSX, and NSC have driven the YoY trend improvement over this period. Even though NSC is improving in this segment, YoY growth remains negative. The 3 carriers with positive YoY growth in Intermodal are CNI, CSX, and CPKC, and the Canadian rails are the leaders. CN, in particular, stands out with L4W Intermodal growth at nearly \(+27\%\) YoY. Western rails continue to experience an Intermodal slowdown, and stand out as the worst-positioned in terms of L4W YoY growth in the segment against peers.

- Merchandise volume has seen a slowdown, with aggregate YoY L4W growth slowing by 60bps from L13W levels of +90bps YoY. All rails, except NSC and CPKC, saw YoY trend deceleration from the L13Ws to the L4Ws. CN and CSX have actually been seeing negative YoY growth in this segment. NSC is the visible winner in L4W Merchandise growth, up nearly 6% YoY, while other positive growth peers are in the LSD-growth range.

EXHIBIT 2: Total North American carload growth has held steady from L13Ws to the L4W period, marking an improvement from Week 33 when we saw YoY trend deceleration from L13Ws to L4Ws. All 3 segments have improved from the prior week's L4W YoY growth levels and now sit in positive growth territory, led by Coal; Merchandise is experiencing the lowest YoY growth of the 3 segments.

Implied Full Quarter Carloads consider how the quarter could shape up if the remaining carloads in this quarter grow at the current QTD YoY rate: In other words, they are based on current QTD carloads plus the current QTD YoY volume growth rate multiplied by the remaining carloads for this quarter last year (i.e. multiplied by last year's volume after the current week). QTD carloads are adjusted for excess / missing days in the quarter coming from start / end weeks of quarter. All other Implied Full Quarter metrics (RPU and Revenue) are then calculated based on the aforementioned assumption for full quarter Carloads. In sum, these Implied Full Quarter numbers are just meant to depict how the full quarter could look if the rest of the quarter trends at similar YoY growth that we've seen so far in the quarter.

Downside risks to our target price for CSX include: changes in government regulation or rule making at the US Surface Transportation Board; changes in governmental clean air regulations and their impact on the coal markets; a slowdown in US or Global economic recovery; geopolitical disturbances that limit global trade flows; ability to recruit, train and staff employees as volume driven growth requires resourcing; inflation in global steel prices; strikes or work stoppages at the company's largely unionized workforce; risks attendant to the company's common carrier obligations and the transportation of hazardous materials. CSX is also a party to a class action suit involving fuel surcharges, and any settlement or adverse ruling from that case is not currently reflected in our estimates.

Upside risks to our estimates are regulation of onshore drilling negatively impact natural gas production, rate of economic recovery in the US accelerating dramatically, and global export coal prices maintaining current high levels.

Risks to our target price for NSC include: changes in government regulation or rule making at the US Surface Transportation Board; changes in governmental clean air regulations and their impact on the coal markets; a slowdown in US or Global economic recovery; geopolitical disturbances that limit global trade flows; ability to recruit, train and staff employees as volume driven growth requires resourcing; inflation in global steel prices; strikes or work stoppages at the company's largely unionized workforce; risks attendant to the company's common carrier obligations and the transportation of hazardous materials. NSC is also a party to a class action suit involving fuel surcharges, and any settlement or adverse ruling from that case is not currently reflected in our estimates. NSC could outperform relative to our estimates should regulation of onshore drilling negatively impact natural gas production, the rate of economic recovery in the US accelerates dramatically, or if there is a disruption in the global supply of metallurgical coal. The most likely sources of underperformance relative to our estimates is a major collapse in export coal demand or a fall of in eastern moves of crude oil by rail.

Downside risks to our target price for UNP include: changes in government regulation or rule making at the US Surface Transportation Board; changes in governmental clean air regulations and their impact on the coal markets; a slowdown in US or Global economic recovery; geopolitical disturbances that limit global trade flows; ability to recruit, train and staff employees as volume driven growth requires resourcing; inflation in global steel prices; strikes or work stoppages at the company's largely unionized workforce; risks attendant to the company's common carrier obligations and the transportation of hazardous materials; ability to retain and re- price legacy energy volumes. Further risks include a more complete collapse of crude by rail (either from economics or from regulation), fall off in Ag pricing due to depressed corn prices, competitive or market driven losses in coal, and the failure of the company to use leverage to repurchase shares.

Downside risks to our target price for CNI include: a material slow down in global economic recovery; changes in government regulation or rule making at either Transport Canada or the US Surface Transportation Board; geopolitical disturbances that limit global trade flows; a slowdown in US or Global economic recovery; strikes or work stoppages at the company's largely unionized

workforce; continued development of export volumes into and out of the Port of Prince Rupert; risks attendant to the company's common carrier obligations and the transportation of hazardous materials. From a sector perspective, a change in the seaborne market for metallurgical coal exports from the United States could impact other competitors in the US rail industry.

Upside risk includes strong rail correlation- as shares of the rail stocks are highly correlated, positive changes in investor sentiment for any of the publicly traded companies in the group could impact the value of CN shares.

Downside risks to our target price for CP include: sustained lower global oil prices; a material slow down in global economic recovery; changes in government regulation or rule making at either Transport Canada or the US Surface Transportation Board; geopolitical disturbances that limit global trade flows; a slowdown in US or global economic recovery; strikes or work stoppages at the company's largely unionized workforce; risks attendant to the company's common carrier obligations and the transportation of hazardous materials; strong dependence of the company's further operational improvement on a few key executives; material changes in foreign exchange rates (appreciation of Canadian Dollar vs US Dollar). CP shares are also exposed to key man risks, and any change in leadership would negatively impact the market's perception of future earnings growth.

Upside risks includes strong rail correlation- as shares of the rail stocks are highly correlated, positive changes in investor sentiment for any of the publicly traded companies in the group could impact the value of CP shares.
